Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content:
**Last Day to Register for CS50M**
**30 NOVEMBER 2019**

Hi all, if considering taking CS50's Mobile App Development with React Native, aka CS50M, via edX, be sure to register by 30 November 2019 at https://cs50.edx.org/mobile. To be eligible for a verified certificate, you'll then need to complete the course by 30 June 2020. Thereafter, the course will no longer be available for a verified certificate from edX, but the course will remain freely available as OpenCourseWare indefinitely.

Because mobile app development is evolving so quickly, the current version of the course is increasingly dated. A new version may take its place, but no timeframe for such just yet!

Author: malan#3259
Content: Like to attend a CS50 lecture at Harvard University this fall? CS50's lectures are open to the public. Whether you are a CS50x student, a CS50 AP student, a prospective student, a teacher, a parent, or a Harvard alum (or anyone else!), you are cordially invited to attend one or more of Fall 2020's lectures in person in Sanders Theatre in Cambridge, Massachusetts, USA. Simply register for a (free) ticket at https://www.eventbrite.com/e/attend-a-cs50-lecture-in-person-tickets-66539606755 once you're certain you can attend! If unable to travel to Cambridge, know that all lectures are also live-streamed at https://cs50.harvard.edu/.

Author: curiouskiwi#1671
Content: Hi everyone. The Academic Honesty guidelines lay out 'not reasonable' activities (https://cs50.harvard.edu/x/2020/syllabus/#not-reasonable)  such as asking for solution code or giving solution code to others.  Please do not post solution code publicly in our channels.   Any that we see will be deleted; please do not spoil the problems for others.  Thanks.

Author: malan#3259
Content:
Hello, @everyone! Just a quick note to say that CS50x Puzzle Day 2020 shall be online-only this year. Team members must NOT gather in person, unless they already live together. All team members must instead collaborate online via chat, voice, or video. Doctors' orders!

Register at https://cs50.ly/register.

Open to everyone around the world, whether taking CS50 or not. Starts anytime after 00:00 on Friday, 3 April 2020, in your own time zone. Ends anytime before 23:59 on Monday, 6 April 2020, in your own time zone.

❤️

Author: malan#3259
Content:
Hello, @everyone! This is CS50's (free) Introduction to Artificial Intelligence with Python, with CS50's own Brian Yu. Available as OpenCourseWare at https://cs50.harvard.edu/ai. Available on edX at https://cs50.edx.org/ai. Starting 1 April 2020. #AI

"This course explores the concepts and algorithms at the foundation of modern artificial intelligence, diving into the ideas that give rise to technologies like game-playing engines, handwriting recognition, and machine translation. Through hands-on projects, students gain exposure to the theory behind graph search algorithms, classification, optimization, reinforcement learning, and other topics in artificial intelligence and machine learning as they incorporate them into their own Python programs. By course’s end, students emerge with experience in libraries for machine learning as well as knowledge of artificial intelligence principles that enable them to design intelligent systems of their own."

Author: malan#3259
Content:
Hello, world! Like to chat via video with Brian and me using Zoom? On Wednesday, 25 March 2020, 1pm EDT – 2pm EDT, Brian and I will be holding "office hours" for students online during which you can ask questions about any of CS50's courses, questions about computer science, questions about programming, or the like. 

To submit a question in advance, submit https://forms.gle/gNDWc1CHM8HZDiPd8. We'll do our best to answer as many as possible! If you have questions about a problem set or project, though, best to post those online at http://cs50.harvard.edu/communities instead!

To attend the office hours, download and install Zoom from https://zoom.us/support/download, test your connection at https://cs50.zoom.us/test, and then log into https://cs50.zoom.us/j/573387876 just before 1pm EDT on Wednesday, 25 March 2020! Or, if your internet connection isn't fast enough for video, you can attend by phone by calling one of these numbers, https://cs50.zoom.us/u/ab1WpXZ9R7.

To convert that date and time into your own time zone, visit https://www.timeanddate.com/worldclock/fixedtime.html?msg=Office+Hours+with+David+and+Brian&iso=20200325T13&p1=797&ah=1.

See you then!

Author: malan#3259
Content:
Hello, world! Each summer, CS50 hosts a workshop (i.e., professional development) for teachers who would like to teach CS50 at their own university, high school, middle school, or community, adopting or adapting its (free) curriculum and tools for their own classes. This year's workshop will be online-only, Thursday, 25 June 2020 – Sunday, 28 June 2020. It will include both prerecorded videos and live video conferences. 

If you (or someone you know) would like to participate, pre-register at https://cs50.ly/preregister, and we'll follow up with more details.

Author: malan#3259
Content:
Hello, world! CS50x Puzzle Day 2020 Online has begun in all time zones! See https://cs50.ly/puzzles for all details, including the puzzles themselves. Be sure to submit your answers by 23:59 on Monday, 6 April 2020. And if you have colleagues or friends who didn't yet register, they're still welcome to register at https://cs50.ly/register and participate.

As you work on the puzzles with teammates, please feel welcome to take photos and screenshots (and even memes) and share them with us at https://cs50.ly/photos as well as in any of CS50's online communities!

https://www.facebook.com/groups/cs50/
https://instagram.com/cs50
https://www.snapchat.com/add/cs50
https://twitter.com/cs50

Best of luck with the puzzles!
